Here's the complete migration:

## Pattern Analysis

Your code has three Thread.Abort APIs that are **all broken on .NET 6+** (`PlatformNotSupportedException` / `SYSLIB0006`):

| API | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----|---------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Timeout enforcement | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Swallow abort | Remove entirely |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);
            task.Wait(cts.Token);       // blocks, throws on cancel
            return task.Result;
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ae) when (ae.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ae.InnerException!);
        }
    }

    // Async overload (preferred for new callers)
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(work, cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

**1. Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive.**
Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancelling the token does **not** interrupt `work()` mid-execution. If `work` is a long-running computation that never checks for cancellation, `Task.Run` will not kill it — the task keeps running in the background. This is the biggest behavioral difference from the original code.

Fix: have `work` accept and check a `CancellationToken`:
```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
        task.Wait(token);
        return task.Result;
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller must cooperate:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();  // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**2. Don't forget to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.**
It creates internal timers — leaking it leaks those timers. Always `using`.

**3. `Task.Wait` wraps exceptions in `AggregateException`.**
The original code threw a bare `AggregateException(innerEx)`. The migrated sync version preserves that. The async version naturally unwraps via `await`.

**4. Truly uncooperative code (can't modify `work`).**
If `work` calls a blocking API you don't control (e.g., native call, third-party library), cooperative cancellation won't help. Move the work to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` — that's the only safe forced-termination mechanism in modern .NET.
